                </div>

                <h4 class="h5 mt-4">Additional Tips for Home Servers</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Port Forwarding:</strong> Configure your router to forward ports 19132 (UDP) for external access</li>
                    <li><strong>Dynamic DNS:</strong> Use a service like No-IP or DuckDNS if you don't have a static IP</li>
                    <li><strong>Firewall:</strong> Ensure Windows Firewall allows the required ports</li>
                    <li><strong>Backups:</strong> Schedule automated backups during off-peak hours</li>
                    <li><strong>Resources:</strong> Monitor CPU/RAM usage to avoid impacting other applications</li>
                </ul>

                <h4 class="h5 mt-4">Port Forwarding Guide</h4>
                <ol>
                    <li>Access your router's admin panel (usually 192.168.1.1 or 192.168.0.1)</li>
                    <li>Find "Port Forwarding" or "Virtual Server" settings</li>
                    <li>Create rules for:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Web UI: TCP port 5000 (optional, for remote management)</li>
                            <li>Minecraft: UDP port 19132 (required for players)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Point to your server's local IP address</li>
                    <li>Save and restart router if needed</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

